  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">On pages 1-2 of this manuscript, there is a letter by Evelina A. S. Smith to Caroline Weston. Evelina begins with a discussion regarding the return of some bags, probably made for the anti-slavery fair. She mentions a plan for a society to educate black people in Liberia and warns against undertaking such a project for reasons of vanity, pride, or ambition. She tells of a man named Brooks who is lecturing on education in Plymouth County.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">On page three, there is a separate note by Increase S. Smith to Caroline Weston. Increase S. Smith comments on Mr. Brooks&apos;s lecture on education, the congregation in Abington, and the fact that he and his wife have not joined the Massachusetts Anti-Slavery Society. He tells about the pleasure he gets from the study of the classics.</subfield>
  </datafield>
